In ROS 2 Actions — There Are TWO Goal Handles
1. Client Side

rclcpp_action::ClientGoalHandle<ActionT>

->This is used by the client.
->It helps the client:
->Track goal status
->Receive feedback
->Get result
->Cancel goal

This is what you are using in:
rclcpp_action::ClientGoalHandle<qt_ros::action::Fibonacci>::SharedPtr
So this is client-side tracking object.

2️.Server Side

On the server side, there is a different class:
rclcpp_action::ServerGoalHandle<ActionT>

This belongs to the server.

It helps the server:

->Accept or reject goal
->Publish feedback
->Succeed / Abort / Cancel goal
->Send result
--------------------------------------------
1. Main Action Type

qt_ros::action::Fibonacci

This is the complete action definition.Inside it, there are 3 important message types.

2. Goal Type

qt_ros::action::Fibonacci::Goal

Data sent from client to server

3. Result Type

qt_ros::action::Fibonacci::Result

Final result sent from server to client

4. Feedback Type

qt_ros::action::Fibonacci::Feedback

Intermediate updates sent while executing

5. ClientGoalHandle Type
rclcpp_action::ClientGoalHandle<qt_ros::action::Fibonacci>

Client-side object that tracks one goal

6. Shared Pointer Types Used in Callbacks

In feedback callback:

A. GoalHandleFibonacci::SharedPtr
B. std::shared_ptr<const qt_ros::action::Fibonacci::Feedback>

In result callback:

GoalHandleFibonacci::WrappedResult

7. Server Side Types (for understanding)

If you write server:
rclcpp_action::ServerGoalHandle<qt_ros::action::Fibonacci>